This is the "Sounds American" channel.

3
00:00:09,900 --> 00:00:14,600
In this video we're going to talk about the American vowel sound /oʊ/,

4
00:00:15,900 --> 00:00:17,740
as in the word "go."

5
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:22,140
You can also hear this sound in words like

6
00:00:22,240 --> 00:00:23,040
"so,"

7
00:00:23,340 --> 00:00:23,980
"snow,"

8
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:25,200
"coat,"

9
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:26,720
or "though."

10
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:33,160
We’ll be using a special phonetic symbol - /oʊ/ - for this sound.

11
00:00:34,040 --> 00:00:40,800
Most non-native English speakers easily distinguish the /oʊ/ sound, but some distort it in speech.

12
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:43,980
Read this phrase aloud.

13
00:00:59,140 --> 00:01:04,160
If you feel you may have mispronounced this vowel sound, keep watching to learn how to fix this.

14
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:07,300
OK.

15
00:01:07,580 --> 00:01:13,260
to pronounce the /oʊ/ sound, you should focus on the correct position of your jaw, lips, and tongue.

16
00:01:17,060 --> 00:01:22,520
Round your lips and make them tense, then pull them in a tighter circle.

17
00:01:28,300 --> 00:01:30,500
Pull your tongue back and tense it.

18
00:01:36,740 --> 00:01:42,160
Remember, the /oʊ/ is a tense sound, so your lips and tongue should be very tense.

19
00:01:44,680 --> 00:01:46,740
Your jaw should be partially lowered.

